<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-10-07T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-10-07T22:00:00-05:00" n="511" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d511">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">882.796/19: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hibbard</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-07T23:00:00-04:00">October 7,
                                    1942—11 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>254. Your 314, September 30. War Department states that permission was
                            granted to the British to refuel at Fisherman’s Lake and to station a
                            few men in civilian clothes there but that it was not the intent of the
                            War Department to grant the British anything in the way of a permanent
                            or large-scale installation. War Department is discussing the matter
                            with British air representatives in Washington and you will be advised
                            as to the results.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>